IBMSTEM4Girls
HTML & CSS Cheat Sheet


HTML:

Document Summary

<html> … </html>
The tag shows up at the beginning and end of an HTML document (known as a root element). 

<title> … </title>
The title tag is the title for the page, it’s used by search engines and users to state the topic of the page

<head> … </head>
This contains the information for the page including the title, meta data, script, and style

<body> ... </body>
Body tags include all content that will be shown to users, including everything you read and see

Document Information

<base>
The Base URL is useful for specifying all relative links in a document

<meta>
Meta data spells out additional information about the page, including the page’s description, author, published date, keywords and other typically 'hidden' information

<link>
Can be used to create relationships with external pages or documents, including style sheets

<style> … </style>
This document includes document style information, typically defaulting to CSS

<script> … </script>
This element includes all scripting information or links to external scripts. You can also include this to dynamically generate content.

Document Structure

<div> … </div>
A generic container used to denote a section of the page

<span> … </span>
An inline section or block container, typically used for grouping styling elements

<h1…h6> … </h1…h6>
All six levels of Headings, with 1 being the most important on the page and 6 being the least. These are used to describe the contents

<p> … </p>
This foundational tag organizes paragraphs of text

<br>
Creates a line break, useful for writing blocks of text that need to be on different lines


<hr>
Creates a horizontal rule, a sectional break in a page. Usually indicates a change in topic or section

<b> … </b>
Creates bolded text

<i> … </i>
Creates italicized text

id=“”
A selector for editing HTML elements in CSS (indicated in the CSS code by #). It can only be used to identify one element

class=“”
A selector for editing HTML elements in CSS (indicated in the CSS code by a .). It can be used for multiple elements

Links

<a href=“”> … </a>
Anchor text for a hyperlink

<a href=“mailto:”> … </a>
A link used to pull up and outgoing message to a specific email address

<a href=“tel://###-###-####”> … </a>
A link to make phone numbers clickable, useful for mobile users

<a name=“name”> … </a>
An anchor that’s useful for bringing users to specific document elements

<a href=“#name”> … </a>
An anchor link that brings users specifically to a div element

Images

<img>
An image tag to include and display image files

src=“url”
The URL or file of the image to display

alt=“text”
Alternative text that helps explain the image content to both search engines and users

height=“” or width=“”
The ability to specify the height or width of an image in pixels or percentages

align=“”
The alignment of the image (relative to other images on the page)

border=“”
Explains border thickness if any

Lists

<ol> … </ol>
Create numbered (ordered) lists showing sequential order

<ul> … </ul>
Display a bulleted (unordered) list without any extra emphasis on order of importance

<li> … </li>
Specifies each list item to be bulleted or numberedCSS:

Syntax
/* Comment */

selector {
	property: values;
	}

